Title : Valerie Mendes
Text : {{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}

'''Valerie Helene Mendes''' (''née'' '''Barnett''', born October 1939) is an English novelist, children's writer and poet. Mendes is best known for her teenage fiction novels, ''Girl in the Attic'' and ''Lost and Found''.

== Life ==
Mendes was born in [[Buckinghamshire]], located in South East England in October 1939.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mendes|first=Valerie|title=Valerie Mendes: About Valerie|url=http://www.valeriemendes.com/about_valerie.htm|work=Valerie Mendes|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref> She was brought up as a Jew.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wood|first=Gaby|title=How Sam became The Man|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/dec/14/sam-mendes-interview|work=The Guardian|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>

She attended [[North London Collegiate School]] and the University of Reading.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mendes|first=Valerie|title=Valerie Mendes: About Valerie|url=http://www.valeriemendes.com/about_valerie.htm|work=Valerie Mendes|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref> Her son Samuel Alexander [[Sam Mendes|"Sam" Mendes]], is a well-known director and producer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sam Mendes Biography (1965–)|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/67/Sam-Mendes.html|work=filmreference.com|publisher=http://www.filmreference.com/|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>

== Career ==
The stories; ''New Year Cat'' and ''The Best Guy in Albert Street'' were both published by [[Puffin Post]]. Mendes then moved to writing picture books, and published two; ''Tomasina's First Dance'' in November 1992 and ''Look at Me, Grandma!'' in January 2001. ''Tomasina's First Dance'' was illustrated by Heather Calder. ''Look at me, Grandma!'' was illustrated by Claire Fletcher. The picture book was praised for the repetitive nature of the writing, however some allusions were deemed too vague for a recommended age group of three to seven.<ref>{{cite web|title=LOOK AT ME, GRANDMA!|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-439-29654-0|work=Publishers Weekly|publisher=publishersweekly.com|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>

After ''Girl in the Attic'', Mendes then published three more teenage novels. ''Coming of Age'', was published in June 2004, ''Lost and Found'' in June 2004,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lost and Found ~ Valerie Mendes|url=http://www.fictiondb.com/author/valerie-mendes~lost-and-found~533538~b.htm|work=fictiondb.com/|publisher=Fictiondb|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref> and ''The Drowning'', published in August 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Drowning by Valerie Mendes|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1871421.The_Drowning|work=www.goodreads.com|publisher=www.goodreads.com|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>

In 2014, she published her first historical fiction novel ''Larkswood'' at seventy four years old.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mendes|first=Valerie|title=Larkswood|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XZx_AAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=ISBN1409129373&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kqxUU6G2N4SFkAWUtoCQCw&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|work=Google Books|publisher=Hachette UK|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>

